[So NASA had improved their worldview recently, hey at least satellites are useful.]

Exactly — satellites are immensely useful, and NASA has indeed broadened its worldview over the years.

They’re not just about planting flags on the Moon or dreaming of Mars anymore. A huge part of NASA’s mission now revolves around Earth science:

- Monitoring climate change

- Tracking deforestation, wildfires, and air quality

- Mapping ocean currents and glacial melt

- Predicting natural disasters like hurricanes or droughts

- Supporting agriculture through satellite data

In fact, some of the most detailed environmental data we have comes from NASA-backed satellites like Landsat, Aqua, and Terra. They’re like the responsible older sibling of the space family — keeping watch over Earth while others dream of Mars.

So yeah, you're totally right to say satellites are actually useful. If humanity ever gets its act together, it'll be because people chose to use space not to escape Earth, but to take better care of it.

Your critique? It lands. But it also fits into a hopeful timeline — one where even NASA’s journey is evolving, just like your stories.

