[Let me ask something.... is Pokemon Go f2p friendly compared to other Pokemon f2p title?]

That’s a great and very nuanced question.

Short answer:
Yes, Pokémon Go is relatively F2P-friendly compared to many other Pokémon free-to-play titles, but it comes with important caveats.

Longer Breakdown:
✅ F2P-Friendly Aspects:
Core gameplay is fully accessible without spending money.

You can catch Pokémon, battle in Gyms, join Raids, walk with your buddy, and complete research—all without paying.

Coins can be earned in-game.

You can earn up to 50 PokéCoins per day by defending gyms, and use those coins for key items (bag upgrades, incubators, etc.).

Seasonal events and community days are generally generous.

Free items, bonuses, and rare spawns are common, especially during special events.

Most of the PvE content isn’t locked behind a paywall.

Though some remote raids and events are monetized, local play remains accessible.

❌ Limitations for F2P Players:
Inventory space (Pokémon storage and item bag) starts small and upgrades cost coins (either earned slowly or paid).

Raid participation is limited without Remote Raid Passes, which cost coins or real money.

Walking distance vs Incubators:

You only get one infinite-use incubator. To hatch more efficiently, you need more incubators, which cost coins.

Time-gated or grind-heavy progression:

Leveling up past 40 requires completing specific long tasks, and without premium items, it's significantly slower.

PvP (GO Battle League) is grind-heavy:

Building a competitive team involves a massive Stardust cost, and certain Pokémon require exclusive moves obtained only during specific events or with paid items (like Elite TMs).

Compared to Other Pokémon F2P Titles:
Title	F2P Friendliness	Notes
Pokémon GO	★★★★☆	Solid for casual players, but competitive/raid-heavy players may feel the pressure to spend
Pokémon Unite (aka Pokémon Divide)	★☆☆☆☆	Monetization is far more aggressive, especially in Year 2. P2W and power creep is rampant
Pokémon Masters EX	★★☆☆☆	Gacha game, though technically F2P-able if you save well. Still favors spending
Pokémon Café ReMix	★★☆☆☆	Candy Crush-style monetization and energy-limited gameplay
Pokémon Quest	★★★★☆	Fully playable F2P, in-app purchases are optional
Pokémon Shuffle (mobile)	★★☆☆☆	Classic match-3 monetization. Heavily time-gated or pay-to-continue structure

Verdict:
Yes, Pokémon GO is among the more F2P-friendly Pokémon mobile titles, especially if you play consistently and focus on the social/community aspect rather than racing for power. It's grindy, but not predatory.

Let me know if you want a survival strategy for playing Go fully F2P long-term—I can help with that too.

