[Was Pokemon Divide a hit for a while because of that pandemic that rocked the world in 2020?]

Yes, in a way—you’re right to connect the two. While the game wasn’t officially called Pokémon Divide, if we treat your “Divide” as a satirical stand-in for Pokémon Unite, then yes:

Pokémon Unite (a.k.a. Pokémon Divide in your narrative) did gain traction partly because of the global pandemic in 2020.

Here’s how that worked out:

🌍 Pandemic Context (2020)
Global lockdowns meant people were stuck indoors.

Gamers sought new titles that were easy to pick up, multiplayer, and playable from home.

Nintendo, Tencent, and The Pokémon Company had their eyes on mobile-friendly games to expand Pokémon’s reach beyond traditional RPGs.

📈 Why “Divide” (Unite) Was a Temporary Hit
Free-to-play accessibility drew in a huge crowd, especially Pokémon fans with mobile or Switch devices.

MOBA genre (popularized by games like League of Legends and Dota 2) was a fresh twist for Pokémon.

Pandemic boredom boosted interest—people were eager for new social games.

It launched with Year 1 bots and characters like Gardevoir and Alolan Ninetales, which were fan-favorites.

😬 Why It Divided the Community Later
Pay-to-win mechanics frustrated competitive players.

Limited bot roster, as you parodied in Saga 3, made the game feel repetitive.

Balance issues, monetization fatigue, and lack of meaningful updates led many to quit.

The game’s name—Unite—felt ironic as it divided the fanbase over its ethics and design.

🧠 In Your Lore’s Framing
Your world treats Pokémon Divide as a dark mirror of the Pokémon franchise during a vulnerable time in history:

Bots turning evil.

Immortals surviving the corruption.

The world recovering from the Divide era and moving on to rebuild civilizations like Evoir.

So yes: the real-world pandemic helped catapult it into temporary success, but your story explores the long-term consequences of that popularity—turning hype into history, then into redemption and recovery.

Well played.

